{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WhRzB42XZh6RigawQirKj1","type":"tool_result","content":"310\t**Given** a new `src/lib/agents/drivers/opencode.ts`\n311\t**When** `dispatch()` is called\n312\t**Then** the driver spawns `opencode` CLI via `child_process.spawn`\n313\t**And** stdout is parsed line-by-line into `StreamEvent` objects\n314\t**And** unparseable lines are logged at debug level and skipped\n315\t**And** a `result` event is always yielded at the end (even on error)\n316\t**And** cost is captured from CLI output or set to `null`\n317\t**And** `healthCheck()` checks `which opencode`, version, and auth status\n318\t**And** missing binary returns `{ available: false, error: \"opencode not found. Install: https://opencode.ai\" }`\n319\t**And** fixture-based tests exist in `test/fixtures/drivers/opencode/`\n320\t\n321\t### Story 3.3: Driver Health Check at Workflow Start\n322\t\n323\tAs a user,\n324\tI want all referenced drivers health-checked before any task executes,\n325\tSo that I get immediate feedback if a CLI is missing or unauthenticated.\n326\t\n327\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n328\t\n329\t**Given** a workflow referencing drivers `claude-code` and `codex`\n330\t**When** `codeharness run` starts\n331\t**Then** the engine calls `healthCheck()` on every unique driver in the workflow\n332\t**And** all health checks complete within 5 seconds total (NFR6)\n333\t**And** if any driver is unavailable, the run aborts with a clear error listing all failing drivers\n334\t**And** if all drivers are healthy, the run proceeds normally\n335\t\n336\t## Epic 4: Cross-Framework Execution & Output Contracts\n337\t\n338\tUsers can run workflows where consecutive tasks use different frameworks with data passing between them.\n339\t\n340\t### Story 4.1: Output Contract Schema & Serialization\n341\t\n342\tAs a developer,\n343\tI want output contracts serialized as JSON files with atomic writes,\n344\tSo that task results survive crashes and can be read by the next task.\n345\t\n346\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n347\t\n348\t**Given** a new `src/lib/agents/output-contract.ts` and `src/schemas/output-contract.schema.json`\n349\t**When** a task completes\n350\t**Then** the engine writes a contract to `.codeharness/contracts/{taskName}-{storyId}.json`\n351\t**And** the write is atomic (write to `.tmp`, then rename)\n352\t**And** the contract includes version, taskName, storyId, driver, model, timestamp, cost_usd, duration_ms, changedFiles, testResults, output, acceptanceCriteria\n353\t**And** fields that aren't available are set to `null`\n354\t**And** serialization/deserialization completes within 1 second for contracts up to 1MB (NFR4)\n355\t\n356\t### Story 4.2: Output Contract Prompt Injection\n357\t\n358\tAs a developer,\n359\tI want the previous task's output contract injected into the next task's prompt,\n360\tSo that cross-framework tasks have context from the previous step.\n361\t\n362\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n363\t\n364\t**Given** a completed task with a written output contract\n365\t**When** the next task in the workflow starts\n366\t**Then** the engine reads the previous contract and formats it as structured prompt context\n367\t**And** the prompt includes changed files, test results, output summary, AC statuses\n368\t**And** the injection is framework-agnostic\n369\t**And** if no previous contract exists (first task), no injection occurs\n370\t\n371\t### Story 4.3: Cross-Framework Workflow Execution\n372\t\n373\tAs a user,\n374\tI want to run a workflow where implement uses claude-code and verify uses codex,\n375\tSo that verification is structurally independent from implementation.\n376\t\n377\t**Acceptance Criteria:**\n378\t\n379\t**Given** a workflow with `implement: { driver: claude-code }` and `verify: { driver: codex }`\n380\t**When** `codeharness run` executes\n381\t**Then** the implement task runs via Claude Code driver\n382\t**And** on completion, an output contract is written\n383\t**And** the verify task starts via Codex driver with the output contract injected\n384\t**And** loop blocks correctly alternate between drivers\n385\t**And** the workflow engine resumes from the last completed task on re-run (NFR18)\n386\t\n387\t## Epic 5: TUI Workflow Visualization\n388\t\n389\tUsers can see the workflow graph in the TUI with current position, driver labels, cost/time, and loop counters."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Cc3NEnB4Yfzm2hoyASCyJg","session_id":"b101ea9e-2f9e-4377-9c5a-f109fa318b32","uuid":"d156d309-bf9e-490a-ac94-1e652ccd490e","timestamp":"2026-04-03T09:37:16.135Z"}
